ounded analysis.\n\n---\n\nHere is a grounded analysis based on the actual codebase, with real byte counts derived from the golden wire format tests.\n\n## Actual overhead breakdown\n\nFrom `GOLDEN_OUTER_ENVELOPE` (93 bytes with 4-byte ciphertext):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| version (2x u8) | 2 |\n| routing_key | 16 |\n| timestamp_hours (varint, current epoch) | 3 |\n| ttl_hours (Some) | 3 |\n| message_id | 16 |\n| ephemeral_key | 32 |\n| ack_hash | 16 |\n| Subtotal outer fixed | **88** |\n\n`InnerEnvelope` fixed overhead (from `GOLDEN_INNER_TEXT` = 46 bytes for \"hi\"):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| from (PublicID) | 32 |\n| created_at_ms (varint) | 6 |\n| Content variant tag | 1 |\n| body length varint | 1 |\n| prev_self None | 1 |\n| observed_heads empty | 1 |\n| epoch (0) | 1 |\n| flags | 1 |\n| Subtotal inner fixed | **44** |\n\nThen: + 64 bytes XEdDSA signature + 16 bytes Poly1305 tag = **80 bytes** crypto overhead on top of serialized inner.\n\nFor \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 bytes UTF-8):\n- Inner serialized: 44 + 1 (varint for len 45) + 45 = **90 bytes**\n- inner_ciphertext: 90 + 64 + 16 = **170 bytes**\n- Wire total: 1 (discriminator) + 88 (outer fixed) + 1 (ciphertext len varint, 2 bytes for >127) + 170 = **261 bytes**\n\nBudget: 237 bytes. Deficit: **~24 bytes** to close.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 1: Pre-encryption compression of InnerEnvelope bytes\n\n**What would actually compress:** The InnerEnvelope postcard output for a typical short message is ~90 bytes. The dominant bytes are:\n- 32-byte `from` PublicID — high entropy, random, **incompressible**\n- 6-byte timestamp varint — low entropy but tiny\n- 64-byte body — natural language text, somewhat compressible\n- remainder — tiny fixed fields\n\nThe 32-byte PublicID alone kills general-purpose compressors. For lz4/deflate/zstd, you'd likely get **0–5 bytes** saved on the inner blob because entropy is dominated by the key bytes. Without a trained dictionary that knows to skip the key, general compression is a net loss (header overhead > savings).\n\nZstd with a **pre-shared dictionary** could theoretically suppress the key bytes, but the dictionary must be known at both ends at compress/decompress time — which is a protocol-level contract and adds a versioning dimension. Savings on 90 bytes with a good dictionary: maybe 10–15 bytes, mostly from the text portion.\n\n**Smaz** (short string compression) works only on the text body, not the whole inner blob. Applied to just the body string, smaz typically achieves 40–50% on English short sentences. For the 45-char example: ~22–27 bytes compressed vs 45. Net saving on total wire size: **~18–22 bytes**. That closes the gap, but Smaz has no Rust crate with active maintenance and is ASCII-only.\n\n**Compression oracle risk:** You note this is not TLS, and there's no cross-message secret reuse in the plaintext, so CRIM********tyle attacks don't apply. Compression before signing is fine here.\n\n**Verdict:** Pre-compression of the whole inner blob is nearly useless. Compressing only the text body with a short-string algorithm like Smaz/shoco is viable but language-dependent and fragile.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 2: Content-level text body compression\n\nThis is the most targeted intervention. The text body is the only variable-length, compressible field.\n\n**Smaz** (Salvatore Sanfilippo's original C lib, 254-symbol codebook):\n- \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 bytes) → typically ~27–30 bytes\n- Savings: ~15–18 bytes\n\n**shoco** (statistical model, trained on English):\n- Similar ratio to Smaz on English text, slightly better on short common phrases\n- ~24–28 bytes for the example\n\n**Custom static dictionary / phrase substitution:**\n- If you control the message corpus (emergency/field comms), a 256-entry phrase table lets you encode \"I'm ok\" as 1 byte, \"meet at\" as 1 byte, etc.\n- 45-char message → plausibly 15–20 bytes with a good domain dictionary\n- Savings: **25–30 bytes** — closes the deficit entirely\n\n**6-bit ASCII packing:** The example string uses only printable ASCII (no high-bit chars). Packing 6 bits/char instead of 8:\n- 45 chars × 6 bits = 270 bits = **33.75 bytes → 34 bytes** (vs 45)\n- Saving: **11 bytes**\n- Trivially implementable, transport-indifferent, no dictionary needed\n- Limitation: no emoji/Unicode, but for LoRa use cases that's acceptable\n\n**Unicode considerations:** All of the above break for non-ASCII. If you need Unicode support, 6-bit packing is out; you'd need a different scheme or a flag indicating encoding type.\n\n**Protocol impact:** Add a new `Content::CompressedText { encoding: CompressionKind, data: Vec<u8> }` variant, or put a flag byte in the existing `TextContent`. The `flags` field in `InnerEnvelope` has bits 1–7 reserved — you could repurpose bit 1 as \"body is 6-bit-packed ASCII\" with zero struct changes.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 3: Structured content types\n\nThis is the highest-leverage approach for constrained-transport use cases. Instead of compressing text, stop sending text.\n\n**Status messages:**\n```rust\npub enum Content {\n    Text(TextContent),\n    Receipt(ReceiptContent),\n    Status(StatusMessage),   // new\n    Location(LocationMessage), // new\n    Template(TemplateMessage), // new\n}\n\npub struct StatusMessage {\n    pub code: StatusCode,  // u8 enum: ImOk, NeedHelp, AtLocation, Evacuating, ...\n    pub location: Option<CompactLocation>,\n}\n\npub struct CompactLocation {\n    pub lat: i32,   // microdegrees: lat * 1e6, fits ±90° in i32\n    pub lon: i32,   // microdegrees: lon * 1e6, fits ±180° in i32\n}\n```\n\n- `StatusCode::ImOk`: 1 byte variant + 1 byte code + 1 byte (None location) = **3 bytes**\n- \"Meet at Central Park at 3pm\":\n  - CompactLocation for Central Park: 8 bytes (2× i32)\n  - Time as minutes-since-midnight u16: 2 bytes (3pm = 900)\n  - Total: ~12–15 bytes with template framing\n\nWire saving vs the 45-char string: **30–40 bytes**, completely