D:** 32 bytes, cryptographically required.\n\n**ephemeral_key:** 32 bytes, cryptographically required.\n\nThe fixed crypto fields (32 + 32 + 16 + 16 + 16 = 112 bytes) are essentially untouchable. The only tunable fixed fields save you 1–3 bytes at most.\n\n---\n\n## Summary and recommendation\n\n| Approach | Implementation effort | Savings (45-char msg) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 6-bit ASCII packing in body | Low (bit manipulation only) | ~11 bytes | ASCII only, flag in existing `flags` byte |\n| Smaz/shoco on body | Medium (add crate, new Content variant) | 15–18 bytes | English only, fragile on other languages |\n| Custom phrase dictionary | Medium | 25–30 bytes | Domain-specific, requires coordinated deploy |\n| Structured content types | Medium-High (new variants + client UI) | 30–40 bytes | The right long-term answer for this use case |\n| Pre-compressing whole inner blob | Not recommended | 0–5 bytes | High-entropy crypto key bytes kill compression |\n| Shrinking fixed outer fields | Low | 1–3 bytes | Minor, worth doing alongside anything else |\n\n**My recommendation:** Do two things:\n\n1. **Immediate/low-risk:** Implement `Content::Status(StatusMessage)` and `Content::MeetAt { location: CompactLocation, time_minutes: u16 }` variants. This covers the canonical LoRa use case (\"I'm ok, meet at X at Y\") in under 15 bytes of content, closing the deficit with room to spare. The `Content` enum is already `#[non_exhaustive]`, the groundwork is there.\n\n2. **As a fallback for freeform text on LoRa:** Implement 6-bit ASCII packing. It's a 30-line encode/decode function, zero dependencies, and reclaims 11 bytes reliably. Signal its use with `FLAG********SCII = 0x02` in the existing `flags` field — no struct changes required. For the 45-char example: 44 + 34 + 64 + 16 + 88 + 2 = 249 bytes, still 12 over budget. Combined with dropping `ttl_hours` for LoRa (save 2 bytes) and reducing timestamp precision (save 1 byte), you land at ~246 bytes — still marginal.\n\nThe honest conclusion: **free-form text of 45+ chars will not fit in 237 bytes on this protocol without structured content types**. 6-bit packing and dictionary compression get you close but not there. Structured messages are the right design for LoRa regardless of compression, because it also enables a better UX (button-based status sends rather than a keyboard on a field device).</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>50588</total_tokens><tool_uses>11</tool_uses><duration_ms>105422</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/9c6dcbb6-96b7-40c7-ac17-633166617352/tasks/afb1bccf808c2dec3.output",
