          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a86c********386e</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********4QLw</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/9c6dcbb6-96b7-40c7-ac17-633166617352/tasks/a86c035d73f9d386e.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Research: how others solve constrained MTU\" completed</summary>\n<result>I have enough data to produce a thorough analysis. Here is the research.\n\n---\n\n## Protocol Comparison: Constrained MTU Encrypted Messaging\n\nThis research compares six protocols against reme's current wire format. The current reme baseline (postcard-serialized `OuterEnvelope` + encrypted `InnerEnvelope`) totals a minimum of roughly **~202 bytes** for a minimal 1-char message (computed below from actual struct fields), and cannot fit in a single LoRa frame at SF10–SF12 (51 bytes) or Meshtastic's worst-case (237 bytes usable after protobuf framing).\n\n### reme Current Overhead (Revised from actual struct)\n\n| Field | Bytes (postcard) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| version (major u8 + minor u8) | 2 | postcard varint, small values = 1B each |\n| routing_key | 16 | fixed `[u8; 16]` |\n| timestamp_hours (u32) | 1–5 | varint; current epoch ~483k hours ≈ 3B |\n| ttl_hours (Option\\<u16\\>) | 1–3 | None = 1B, Some(x) = 2–3B |\n| message_id | 16 | `[u8; 16]` |\n| ephemeral_key | 32 | `[u8; 32]` |\n| ack_hash | 16 | `[u8; 16]` |\n| inner_ciphertext (length prefix) | 1–3 | postcard varint length |\n| **OuterEnvelope fixed** | **~87 bytes** | |\n| InnerEnvelope.from (PublicID) | 32 | sender's X25519 pubkey |\n| InnerEnvelope.created_at_ms | 1–9 | varint; current ms epoch ≈ 6B |\n| InnerEnvelope.prev_self (Option) | 1–9 | None = 1B |\n| InnerEnvelope.observed_heads (Vec) | 1 | empty = 1B length prefix |\n| InnerEnvelope.epoch (u16) | 1–3 | |\n| InnerEnvelope.flags | 1 | |\n| Content discriminant + text len + 1 char | ~4 | postcard enum + varint + byte |\n| **InnerEnvelope serialized** | **~50 bytes** | minimum |\n| XEdDSA signature (appended pre-encrypt) | 64 | |\n| ChaCha20-Poly1305 tag | 16 | |\n| **Total minimum** | **~217 bytes** | 1-char text message |\n\nThe existing analysis documents in the repo cite ~252 bytes from an older struct layout. The current optimized struct is closer to 217 bytes but still exceeds Meshtastic's 237-byte usable payload for any message with more than about 20 characters.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Meshtastic\n\n**Crypto overhead breakdown:**\n\n| Layer | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| PacketHeader (to, from, id, flags, channel, next_hop, relay_node) | 16 |\n| Extra nonce (random, v2.5+ DM) | 4 |\n| AES-CCM MAC tag | 8 |\n| **PKC (MESHTASTIC_PKC_OVERHEAD)** | **12 total (nonce 4 + MAC 8)** |\n| X25519 public key (broadcast separately, NOT per-message) | 0 |\n| **Per-DM overhead above header** | **12 bytes** |\n| **Total wire overhead** | **16 + 12 = 28 bytes** |\n\nMax LoRa payload: 255 bytes. After header (16) and PKC overhead (12): **227 bytes available for protobuf content**.\n\nThe sender's public key is broadcast as part of periodic NodeInfo packets, not included in each DM. The recipient uses the stored key to re-derive the shared secret. This is the key space-saving design decision.\n\n**Security properties:**\n- Confidentiality: yes (AES-256-CCM)\n- Integrity: yes (CCM MAC, 8 bytes)\n- Sender authentication: weak — TOFU model; no signature per message; sender identity is the \"from\" field in the unencrypted header\n- Non-repudiation: none\n- Replay protection: packet ID in nonce prevents replay for same packet, but no full sequence numbering per conversation\n- Forward secrecy: none (static X25519 key pair per node, no ratchet)\n\n**What Meshtastic sacrifices:** Forward secrecy, non-repudiation, strong sender authentication (no per-message signature), and resistance to a MITM who captured the static key. They accept TOFU because a PKI does not fit in 255 bytes and IoT hardware lacks the entropy/memory.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** Meshtastic eliminates the per-message ephemeral key (32 bytes) by using long-term static X25519 keys. They broadcast the public key once and reuse it. The shared secret is static per pair. This saves 32 bytes per message at the cost of forward secrecy. For reme's constrained profile, a similar \"session mode\" — negotiate once, encrypt subsequent messages with a derived counter key — would reduce OuterEnvelope by at least 32 bytes (remove ephemeral_key) plus 16 bytes (remove ack_hash if not needed for that transport).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Signal Protocol (Sealed Sender / X3DH)\n\nSignal is designed for high-bandwidth transports (MTU ~1500 bytes). The minimum first-message overhead:\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| Sender's ephemeral key EK_A | 32 |\n| Sender's identity key IK_A | 32 |\n| One-time prekey ID | 4 |\n| Double Ratchet header (ratchet pubkey + chain/msg index) | 32 + 8 = 40 |\n| AES-********/GCM ciphertext auth tag | 16 |\n| **First message total overhead** | **~124 bytes** |\n\nAfter the handshake, steady-state Double Ratchet messages carry:\n- 32 bytes ratchet public key (sent on each ratchet step)\n- 8 bytes message/chain counters\n- 16 bytes AEAD tag\n- = **56 bytes per DR step**, or **24 bytes** in the same ratchet chain (no new DH key needed)\n\nSealed sender adds a further ~53 bytes (encrypted sender certificate wrapping the above).\n\nSignal's 160-byte padding granularity is a deliberate bandwidth-versus-traffic-analysis tradeoff that would be devastating on LoRa (a 1-char message becomes 160 bytes of plaintext before encryption).\n\n**Security properties vs reme:**\n- Forward secrecy: yes (Double Ratchet provides per-message FS)\n- Break-in recovery (post-compromise security): yes\n- Non-repudiation: none by design (deniable authentication)\n- Sender anonymity from server: yes (sealed sender)\n\n**What Signal sacrifices for constraints:** Nothing — Signal does not target constrained transports. The ~124-byte handshake already exceeds LoRa SF10–12 (51 bytes) and exactly fits Meshtastic only for the first message with minimal plaintext.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** Signal's Double Ratchet at steady state costs only **24–56 bytes overhead** (no new DH + 16-byte tag), which is far more compact than reme's per-message ephemeral key (32 bytes) because Signal amortizes DH across many messages. If reme introduced a session-level ratchet state (even a simple symmetric ratchet / KDF chain without DH), it could cut per-message overhead from ~87 to ~40 bytes for the outer envelope on established sessions.\n\n---\n\n## 3. COSE_Encrypt0 (RFC 9052/9053)\n\nMinimal `COSE_Encrypt0` with AES-GCM-128, pre-shared key, and a 12-byte IV:\n\n| Component | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| CBOR tag `#6.16` (tagged form) | 1 |\n| CBOR 3-element array header | 1 |\n| Protected header bstr (alg=A128GCM, IV) | ~18 (1 bstr header + 1 map header + 1 alg id + 1 alg value + 1 IV header + 12 IV value) |\n| Unprotected header (empty map) | 1 |\n| Ciphertext bstr header | 1–3 |\n| AES-GCM auth tag (appended to ciphertext) | 16 |\n| **Total non-payload overhead** | **~38–42 bytes** |\n\nThis is the minimum overhead for an AEAD-encrypted blob with a pre-shared key. No sender identity, no key derivation, no routing.\n\nIf the IV is placed in the unprotected header (allowed and common), the protected header shrinks to ~4 bytes and total non-payload overhead drops to **~28–32 bytes** — but then the IV is malleable (though GCM decryption will fail with a wrong IV, so this is acceptable for AEAD).\n\n**Security properties vs reme:**\n- Confidentiality: yes\n- Integrity: yes (GCM tag)\n- Sender authentication: none (pre-shared key only, no identity)\n- Non-repudiation: none\n- No routing metadata, no nonce management beyond the app-provided IV\n\n**What COSE_Encrypt0 sacrifices:** Everything above the transport layer. It is a bare wire-format for AEAD, not a messaging protocol. Routing, identity, replay protection, and sender auth are all left to the application.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** reme's current binary format (postcard) is already more compact than COSE_Encrypt0 for the pure ciphertext wrapper (~6 bytes postcard header vs ~28 bytes COSE). COSE is relevant only if interoperability with IoT ecosystems (OSCORE, Matter, CoAP) is a goal. COSE's main benefit is a well-known, tooled format — not byte efficiency.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Noise Protocol Framework (Noise_X)\n\nNoise_X with Curve25519 + ChaChaPoly, one-way (initiator sends to responder, no response needed):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| Ephemeral public key `e` (cleartext) | 32 |\n| Encrypted static key `s` (32 key + 16 AEAD tag) | 48 |\n| Payload AEAD tag | 16 |\n| **Fixed overhead** | **96 bytes** |\n\nFor a message with N bytes of plaintext: **N + 96 bytes total**.\n\nNoise_NK (initiator knows responder's static key, no static key sent):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| Ephemeral public key `e` (cleartext) | 32 |\n| Payload AEAD tag | 16 |\n| **Fixed overhead** | **48 bytes** |\n\nNoise_NK is the minimum one-way pattern when the sender already knows the recipient's static key (equivalent to reme's current MIK model). This is directly comparable to reme's current ephemeral_key (32) + AEAD tag (16) = **48 bytes of pure crypto overhead**, which matches Noise_NK exactly.\n\n**Security properties:**\n- Noise_X: provides sender authentication (static key in ciphertext), confidentiality, integrity, forward secrecy for the session\n- Noise_NK: confidentiality + integrity; no sender identity transmitted; equivalent to reme's sealed box approach\n- No non-repudiation by design (Noise is deniable)\n\n**What Noise sacrifices:** Non-repudiation; higher-level protocol concerns (routing, timestamps, TTL). Noise produces a raw session channel, not a messaging envelope.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** reme's current OuterEnvelope crypto is functionally Noise_NK with extra metadata. The pure crypto cost is already at the Noise minimum. The overhead problem is entirely in the metadata layer: routing_key (16), message_id (16), ack_hash (16), timestamp_hours (3), ttl_hours (2) = **53 bytes of non-crypto metadata** that has no counterpart in Noise. A constrained profile stripping most of this metadata would reach ~87 bytes total overhead.\n\n---\n\n## 5. LoRaWAN MAC Layer\n\nLoRaWAN is a coordinated LPWAN protocol with a central network server. Its frame structure:\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| MHDR (frame type + version) | 1 |\n| DevAddr (device address) | 4 |\n| FCtrl (ADR, ACK flags) | 1 |\n| FCnt (frame counter, replay protection) | 2 |\n| FPort (application port) | 1 |\n| MIC (AES-CMAC truncated to 4 bytes) | 4 |\n| **Total MAC overhead** | **13 bytes** |\n\nApplication payload is encrypted with AES-128-CTR using AppSKey. The MIC is computed over the entire frame using NwkSKey (or FNwkSIntKey in v1.1). No public key exchange per frame — keys are provisioned at device join (OTAA) or hardcoded (ABP).\n\nThe 4-byte MIC is a truncated CMAC, providing 32-bit authentication strength. This is weak by modern standards (birthday bound ~65K messages before collision probability becomes non-trivial), but acceptable for telemetry in a managed network. At SF7 (best case): 242 bytes available, of which 13 go to MAC overhead = **229 bytes for application data**.\n\n**Security properties vs reme:**\n- Confidentiality: yes (AES-128-CTR)\n- Integrity/authenticity: weak (4-byte MAC)\n- Sender authentication: via DevAddr + keys provisioned at join; no per-message identity proof\n- Non-repudiation: none\n- Forward secrecy: none (static session keys)\n- Sender anonymity: none (DevAddr transmitted cleartext; linkable)\n- E2E encryption: optional (LoRaWAN encrypts only to network server; AppSKey provides E2E to application server if key not shared with network)\n\n**What LoRaWAN sacrifices:** Strong authentication (4-byte MAC), forward secrecy, sender anonymity, decentralization (requires network server), and any concept of sender identity at the protocol level. It is optimized purely for IoT telemetry in a managed infrastructure context.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** LoRaWAN's 13-byte overhead is achievable only because sender identity is pre-provisioned and never transmitted per-message, key exchange happens at join (not per-message), and authentication strength is deliberately weakened (4 bytes). For a decentralized messenger where sender identity matters, this is the absolute floor — and it only works with infrastructure. The lesson: a managed/paired-device profile (both parties pre-exchange keys and assign a compact DevAddr equivalent) could approach 13–20 bytes of per-message overhead, sufficient for SF10–SF12.\n\n---\n\n## 6. DTN Bundle Protocol / BPSec (RFC 9171/9172/9173)\n\nBPSec BCB-AES-GCM minimum overhead for authenticated encryption of a bundle block:\n\n| Component | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| IV/nonce (minimum 8, recommended 12 bytes) | 9–14 (with CBOR header) |\n| AES-GCM auth tag (16 bytes + 1 CBOR header) | 17 |\n| BCB extension block framing (type, block #, flags, CRC type, length) | 5–7 |\n| Abstract security block (target list, context ID, flags, source EID) | 10–15 |\n| **Minimum BCB overhead** | **~43–53 bytes** |\n\nBPSec also defines a Block Integrity Block (BIB) for integrity-only (no encryption), using HMAC-SHA2 with a minimum overhead of ~40 bytes.\n\nBPv7 primary block itself costs ~20–30 bytes (CBOR array with 8–11 fields including source/dest EIDs). A full bundle with BCB protection and a short EID scheme starts at about **70–100 bytes** total overhead before any payload.\n\n**Security properties vs reme:**\n- Confidentiality: yes (AES-GCM)\n- Integrity: yes (GCM tag, bound via AAD to bundle identity)\n- Sender authentication: via BIB (separate integrity block) or pre-shared key; no PKI defined in base RFC — RFC 9173 uses symmetric keys only\n- Non-repudiation: not addressed (out of scope for BPSec)\n- Forward secrecy: not addressed\n- Store-and-forward: first-class design goal (handles arbitrarily long custody chains)\n\n**What BPSec sacrifices:** PKI/asymmetric sender authentication in the base spec (RFC 9173 is symmetric-key only). Forward secrecy is not in scope. The CBOR encoding adds framing overhead vs a custom binary format.\n\n**Key insight for reme:** BPSec's AAD-based integrity binding (the MAC covers the primary block, so a BCB cannot be replayed to a different bundle or destination) is directly applicable to reme. reme currently achieves similar binding by including `outer_message_id` in the AEAD AAD during encryption (see `reme-encryption`). The BPSec pattern of having a separate BIB (integrity-only) and BCB (confidentiality) is worth considering for reme's relay architecture: intermediate nodes could verify BIB without decrypting BCB, enabling authenticated routing without revealing content.\n\n---\n\n## Comparative Summary Table\n\n| Protocol | Crypto/envelope overhead | Sender auth | Forward secrecy | Non-repudiation | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **reme current** | ~217 bytes min | XEdDSA (64B sig) | none | yes (sig) | Exceeds Meshtastic for 20+ char messages |\n| **Meshtastic DM (v2.5)** | 28 bytes (16 header + 12 PKC) | TOFU only | none | none | No per-message sig; static key pair |\n| **Signal DR (steady state)** | 24–56 bytes | Deniable (KDF) | per-message | none | Not designed for constrained MTU |\n| **Signal first message** | ~124 bytes | Deniable | yes | none | Exceeds Meshtastic |\n| **Noise_X** | 96 bytes | Authenticated | session-level | none | Sender static key in ciphertext |\n| **Noise_NK** | 48 bytes | None (anonymous) | none | none | Equivalent to reme outer crypto only |\n| **COSE_Encrypt0 (PSK)** | ~28–42 bytes | none | none | none | Bare AEAD wrapper, no identity |\n| **LoRaWAN MAC** | 13 bytes | Pre-provisioned | none | none | Infrastructure-dependent, 4B MAC only |\n| **BPSec BCB** | ~43–53 bytes | Symmetric-key BIB | none | none | CBOR overhead, store-and-forward focus |\n\n---\n\n## What reme Could Borrow\n\n**1. Meshtastic's static session key model for constrained profiles**\nFor the LoRa/constrained transport profile, pre-negotiate a shared session key (exchange once via an unconstrained channel), then drop the per-message `ephemeral_key` (saves 32 bytes) and `ack_hash` (saves 16 bytes). Per-message overhead drops from ~87 to ~39 bytes for the outer envelope, putting a ~180-byte full message within Meshtastic's 237-byte window with the signature, or a ~115-byte message without it.\n\n**2. Signal's symmetric ratchet for forward secrecy without per-message DH**\nA simple HKDF chain (no DH per message, just KDF(prev_key || counter) → next_key) adds zero per-message overhead after session establishment. This gives forward secrecy on established sessions without any extra bytes. reme already has `epoch` and DAG ordering — the chain key could be derived from the same material.\n\n**3. Meshtastic/LoRaWAN's approach to sender identity: broadcast once, reference cheaply**\nBoth Meshtastic and LoRaWAN never transmit the full sender public key per message. Meshtastic includes it in NodeInfo beacons; LoRaWAN provisions at join. For reme, a \"contact established\" state could replace the 32-byte `from` field in InnerEnvelope with a 4–8 byte session token or eliminate it entirely (the shared secret already implies the sender).\n\n**4. Noise_NK's observation that 48 bytes is the crypto floor for anonymous AEAD with a known recipient key**\nreme's current outer crypto is already at this floor. The optimization headroom is entirely in the metadata. The constrained profile should strip: `message_id` (use counter), `ack_hash` (use out-of-band ack), `timestamp_hours` (derive from network time), `ttl_hours` (fixed for constrained transport) = saves ~51 bytes.\n\n**5. BPSec's BIB pattern for relay authentication without content exposure**\nRelay nodes currently trust that a message is legitimate based only on routing_key lookup. A lightweight BIB-equivalent (HMAC over outer fields, verifiable without decryption, using a shared relay key) would let relays reject forged or replayed routing metadata without seeing the payload. This is additive overhead (~32 bytes for an HMAC-SHA256 truncated to 16 bytes + minimal framing) but enables authenticated gossip routing.\n\n---\n\nSources:\n- [Meshtastic Encryption Docs](https://meshtastic.org/docs/overview/encryption/)\n- [Meshtastic PKC v2.5 Blog Post](https://meshtastic.org/blog/introducing-new-public-key-cryptography-in-v2_5/)\n- [Meshtastic Updated Security Implementation](https://meshtastic.org/docs/development/reference/encryption-technical/)\n- [meshtastic/firmware DeepWiki (packet layout)](https://deepwiki.com/search/what-is-the-exact-byte-layout_511b11ae-47fa-4366-bd11-3688bffaf4cb)\n- [Signal Sealed Sender Blog](https://signal.org/blog/sealed-sender/)\n- [Signal X3DH Spec](https://signal.org/docs/specifications/x3dh/)\n- [Signal Double Ratchet Spec](https://signal.org/docs/specifications/doubleratchet/)\n- [Noise Protocol Framework Spec](https://noiseprotocol.org/noise.html)\n- [RFC 9052 COSE Structures](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/rfc9052/)\n- [RFC 9053 COSE Algorithms](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/rfc9053/)\n- [RFC 9172 BPSec](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9172)\n- [RFC 9173 BPSec Default Security Contexts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/rfc9173/)\n- [LoRaWAN Frame Overhead Analysis](https://eadalabs.com/lorawan-overhead/)\n- [LoRaWAN Security (TTN)](https://www.thethingsnetwork.org/docs/lorawan/security/)\n- [LoRaWAN Whitepaper (LoRa Alliance)](https://lora-alliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/lorawan_security_whitepaper.pdf)\n- [Improving Signal's Sealed Sender (NDSS 2021)](https://www.ndss-symposium.org/ndss-paper/improving-signals-sealed-sender/)</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>65429</total_tokens><tool_uses>27</tool_uses><duration_ms>529113</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/9c6dcbb6-96b7-40c7-ac17-633166617352/tasks/a86c035d73f9d386e.output",
