          "text": "All 4 agents done. Let me synthesize.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis: how to fit more into a single LoRa frame\n\n**Current budget:** 237 bytes (Meshtastic). Current overhead: **~213 bytes**. Leaves ~24 bytes for text.\n\n**Target:** \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" = 45 bytes. Need ~21 more bytes.\n\n### The menu, ranked by bytes saved / complexity\n\n| Change | Bytes saved | Complexity | Tradeoff |\n|--------|------------|------------|----------|\n| **routing_key 16→8** | 8 | Trivial | Collision P ≈ 2.7×10⁻⁸ at 1M users |\n| **message_id 16→8** | 8 | Trivial | Collision safe with TTL-bounded stores |\n| **ack_hash 16→8** | 8 | Trivial | 2⁶⁴ preimage resistance, sufficient |\n| **XEdDSA → BLAKE3 MAC 16B** | 48 | Low | Lose non-repudiation (not a requirement) |\n| **XEdDSA → BLAKE3 MAC 32B** | 32 | Low | Same, more conservative |\n| **created_at_ms → created_at_s offset** | 2 | Low | Lose ms precision |\n| **version 2B → 1B** | 1 | Trivial | Nibble-packed major.minor |\n| **ttl_hours → ttl_days Option\\<u8\\>** | 1 | Low | Day-granularity TTL |\n| **6-bit ASCII body packing** | ~25% of body | Low | ASCII only, flag in existing `flags` |\n| **from 32B → 8B hint** | 24 | Medium | Needs contact-lookup; first msg still full |\n| **Drop ephemeral_key (session mode)** | 32 | High | Needs session establishment, loses statelessness |\n\n### Three tiers of approach\n\n**Tier 1: Field truncation only (zero semantic change)**\nrouting_key + message_id + ack_hash: 16→8 each = **24 bytes saved**.\nNew overhead: ~189 bytes. Available for text: **~48 bytes**. This alone fits the 45-char example.\n\n**Tier 2: Tier 1 + MAC instead of signature**\nReplace 64-byte XEdDSA with 16-byte BLAKE3-keyed MAC = **48 more bytes saved**.\nNew overhead: ~141 bytes. Available for text: **~96 bytes**. Fits a full paragraph. Loses non-repudiation, which isn't in the threat model.\n\n**Tier 3: Tier 2 + minor field optimizations**\nAdd version packing, timestamp seconds, ttl_days = **~4 more bytes**.\nNew overhead: ~137 bytes. Available for text: **~100 bytes**. Comfortable margin.\n\n### What NOT to do\n- Structured content types (Status/Location) — can't enumerate what people want to say\n- Pre-encryption compression — incompressible 32-byte PublicID kills it\n- Transport-specific envelopes — breaks the core invariant\n- Drop ephemeral_key — kills statelessness, the entire DTN design\n- Truncate Poly1305 tag — 8 bytes not worth the security regression\n\n### Key insight from external research\n\nNoise_NK proves the **crypto floor is 48 bytes** (32 ephemeral + 16 AEAD tag). reme is already at that floor for the crypto layer. The excess is entirely **metadata** (routing_key, message_id, ack_hash, timestamps = 53 bytes). Truncating these three 16-byte fields to 8 bytes each is the single highest-leverage change with zero security or protocol impact.\n\n### My recommendation\n\n**Tier 1 is the clear winner** — 24 bytes saved by changing three array sizes from `[u8; 16]` to `[u8; 8]`. No semantic changes, no crypto changes, no protocol flow changes. Gets the 45-char message to fit in a single LoRa frame. This is a breaking change (wire format), which is fine in PoC.\n\n**Tier 2 (MAC)** is worth designing but is a bigger decision — changes the crypto model. Could be done later if more headroom is needed.\n\nWant me to write up a plan for the Tier 1 field truncation?",
