e-peer lifecycle with `failure_count` and `FAILURE_THRESHOLD`, `verified_peer_index` for multi-device tracking, config rename `allow_direct_lan` to `auto_direct_known_contacts`. All plan items delivered.\n- **Unit 7 (Client runtime)**: Dynamic contact channel (`mpsc::UnboundedSender`), TUI peer count in status bar via `AtomicUsize`, mDNS failure notice via `InitResult::Failed`, migration to `send_text_tiered`. All plan items delivered.\n- **Unit 8 (Transport registry)**: Read-only view with `with_coordinator()`, mutation methods removed, `MessageReceiver` deprecated with `#[deprecated]` attributes. All plan items delivered.\n- **Unit 9 (Node API & docs)**: `sign_data.zeroize()` added, threat model updated (MAX_PEERS reference fixed, contact-graph edge mention added, channel binding status clarified), `#[allow(deprecated)]` added to integration tests for `MessageReceiver`. All plan items delivered.\n\n### No Deviations Found\n\nThe implementation tracks the plan faithfully. I found no meaningful deviations -- only additive improvements (extra tests, better docs) that are strictly beneficial.\n\n---\n\n## Code Quality Assessment\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n1. **Timing oracle fix** (`controller.rs:544-552`): The full-iteration pattern correctly prevents timing-based information leakage. The `matched.is_none()` guard ensures only the first match is recorded while still iterating all candidates. This is the correct approach.\n\n2. **`DiscoveryState` struct** (`discovery/mod.rs`): Clean extraction of three scattered `Option` fields into a cohesive struct. The `InitResult` enum is a good pattern -- it distinguishes disabled/failed/ok without conflating states.\n\n3. **Periodic refresh with circuit breaker** (`controller.rs:187-242`): The collect-first-then-mutate pattern avoids borrow conflicts cleanly. The `FAILURE_THRESHOLD` constant and `failure_count` tracking is straightforward and correct.\n\n4. **`TransportRegistry` read-only view** (`registry.rs`): The separation of concerns is good -- the registry reads from coordinator pools via `Arc` references. The `EnrichedSnapshot` type properly layers metadata on top of transport snapshots.\n\n5. **Test coverage**: New tests cover multi-device tracking, failure count initialization, peer removal, metadata-only targets in health summary, and `list_targets`/`has_available` consistency. The test-per-behavior approach is solid.\n\n6. **Documentation**: Function-level doc comments are thorough and include rationale (e.g., the `TODO(#90)` comment on receipt-gated direct tier, the `FIXME(SEC-3)` on channel binding). The threat model updates are well-written.\n\n---\n\n## Issues\n\n### Important (should fix)\n\n**I1. `has_available()` returns `true` for metadata-only targets with `HealthState::Unknown`**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/registry.rs`, line 308\n\n```rust\nlet has_meta_targets = !self.target_meta.read().unwrap().is_empty();\nhttp_available || mqtt_available || has_meta_targets\n```\n\nA metadata-only target (no pool backing) has `HealthState::Unknown`. If `has_available()` returns `true` based solely on metadata presence, callers may attempt delivery to targets that have no actual transport backing. This could cause confusing behavior if the registry has stale metadata entries after targets are removed from the coordinator. The test at line 461 explicitly validates this behavior, suggesting it was intentional -- but the semantic mismatch between \"available\" and \"unknown health\" is worth a comment explaining the design intent. If this is by design (e.g., metadata-only targets are always send-only LAN peers that the coordinator routes through), document that assumption.\n\n**I2. `verified_peer_index` uses `Vec<String>` -- O(n) removal**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, lines 442-446, 475-479\n\nThe `verified_peer_index: HashMap<PublicID, Vec<String>>` uses `retain` for removal, which is O(n) per instance name. With the `max_peers` cap of 256 and typical multi-device counts of 2-3, this is fine in practice. But if multi-device counts grow or the peer limit increases, a `HashSet<String>` would be more appropriate. Not blocking, but worth a `// NOTE: Vec is fine for typical multi-device counts (2-3)` comment.\n\n**I3. Dynamic contact deduplication**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, line 136\n\n```rust\ncontroller.contact_index.entry(routing_key).or_default().push(pubkey);\n```\n\nIf the same contact is added multiple times via `contact_rx` (e.g., user adds the same contact twice in the TUI), the same `PublicID` will appear multiple times in the candidates vector. This causes redundant verification work in `verify_peer_identity`. The initial contacts in `new()` have the same issue if duplicates are passed. Consider deduplicating (e.g., check `contains` before push), or document that duplicates are harmless.\n\n### Suggestions (nice to have)\n\n**S1. `refresh_all_peers` could parallelize verification**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, lines 207-231\n\nCurrently, refresh re-verifies peers sequentially. With a 5-second per-request timeout and 256 max peers, worst case is ~21 minutes for a single refresh cycle. For typical deployments (a few peers) this is fine. If peer counts grow, consider `futures::stream::FuturesUnordered` for concurrent verification. Not blocking for now.\n\n**S2. Config `refresh_interval_secs` of 0 not validated**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/config.rs`, line 464\n\nA user setting `refresh_interval_secs = 0` would create a `tokio::time::interval(Duration::from_secs(0))`, which ticks immediately and continuously -- effectively a tight loop. Consider clamping to a minimum (e.g., 30 seconds) similar to how `max_peers` is clamped from 0 to 1.\n\n**S3. `register_stable` method appears unused**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/registry.rs`, lines 111-125\n\n`register_stable` is defined but I see no call sites in the diff. It may be intended for future use (config-file targets), but if it is dead code today, consider marking it with `#[allow(dead_code)]` or removing it until needed. Verify whether it has call sites elsewhere in the codebase.\n\n**S4. Threat model -- minor wording**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/docs/threat-model.md`, line 24\n\n> The receipt signature (XEdDSA over domain-separated `signer_pubkey || message_id`) is verified and recorded but does **not** gate tier success.\n\nThe wording \"is verified and recorded\" could be misread as meaning verification happens. Suggest: \"The receipt signature is **checked if present** but does **not** gate tier success.\"\n\n---\n\n## Architecture and Design Review\n\nThe architecture is sound:\n\n- **Separation of concerns**: Discovery (mDNS) -> Controller (verification/lifecycle) -> Coordinator (transport management) -> Registry (read-only view). Each layer has clear responsibilities.\n- **Concurrency model**: `broadcast::channel` for discovery events, `mpsc::unbounded_channel` for dynamic contacts, `AtomicUsize` for peer count -- all appropriate choices for their use cases.\n- **Security posture**: The timing oracle fix, body size cap, `zeroize` on `sign_data`, and the threat model documentation show security-conscious development. The `FIXME(SEC-3)` and `TODO(#90)` annotations correctly track known gaps.\n- **Graceful shutdown**: The controller drains and deregisters all peers, resets the peer count, and logs shutdown. The `CancellationToken` pattern is consistently applied.\n\n---\n\n## Verification Results\n\n```\ncargo test --workspace: PASS (all tests pass)\ncargo clippy --workspace: PASS (no warnings)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Verdict\n\nThe implementation is thorough, well-documented, and faithful to the plan. The code quality is high with good test coverage and security-conscious design. The three \"Important\" items (I1-I3) are edge cases that should be addressed (even if just with comments documenting intentional behavior), but none are blocking. The suggestions (S1-S4) are genuinely optional improvements.\n\nThe branch is in good shape for merging into `feat/lan-discovery`.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>76733</total_tokens><tool_uses>39</tool_uses><duration_ms>344311</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/a549db376cafa4feb.output",
